### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: 322<n><n>Input: Josh’s mom gives him $20 to go shopping at the mall. He buys a hat for $10 and a pencil for $2. Then he buys four cookies. If each cookie costs $1.25, how much money does Josh have left?<n>Output: 3<n><n>Input: George's bowling team is one round away from breaking the league record for most points scored in a season. The old record is an average score per player of 287 per round. Each team has 4 players and there are 10 rounds in the season. Through the first 9 rounds, his team has scored a total of 10,440. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. It took him 20 minutes to finish tasks from biology and two times more time to finish history. Geography took him the most time, three times more than history. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. If the pie left in the fridge weighs 1200 grams, how many grams did Sophia eat?<n>Output: 240<n><n>Input: Sarah, Mary, and Tuan decided to go to the restaurant for a meal. They decided to split the cost of the meal evenly. If the total price of the meal comes to $67 and they have a coupon for $4, how much does each person need to contribute to the bill?<n>Output: 21<n><n>Input: Tom's brother is 4 times as old as Tom's dog. If in 6 years, Tom's brother will be 30 years, how old is Tom's dog going to be in six years?<n>Output: 12<n><n>Input:Sammy wanted to go to where the people were.  Where might he go? Choices:  A: race track B: populated areas C: the desert D: apartment E: roadblock<n>Output:		A<n><n>Input: Sammy heard that the animals were in a park nearby.  Why did Sammy want to find the animals? Choices:  Sammy likes animals A: so he can help them B: because he likes to watch them C: he does not know why Choices: A<n>Output: B<n><n>Input: The teacher asked her classes to name the planets in the solar system. Choices:  A; A, B, C, D; A, B, E, F Choices:  B, C, D, E<n>Output: B<n>

For example, the answer is "I have five dogs."<n><n>### Question:  <n>This is a question that is a question about counting, but does not relate to your job.<n><n>### Example answer: <n>Sarah asked Tom how much he owed and Dave said that he did not know.<n><n>### Challenge:<n>Try to reduce the code for each solution.  Be careful to test your code - and do your best to be clear.<n><n>### Solution: <n><n>```python<n>import math<n>from string import strip<n>while True:<n>    try:<n>        answer = float(input('Question: '))<n>        answer = answer * 100 <n>        break<n>    except ValueError:<n>        print('Type float.')<n>        continue<n><n>"""Part A"""<n><n>def get_total(string):<n>    """Takes a string of numbers, returns total and amount owed."""<n>    n = 0 # Number of digits<n>    res = 0 # Resulting value<n>    while n < len(string):<n>        n += 1<n>        b = int(string[n-2])<n>        d = int("".join([char for char in string[n:-2] if char=='0']))<n>        res += b + (b/10 * d)<n>    return res + (len(string)-1)<n><n>"""Part B"""<n><n>def sum_digits(string):<n>    n = 1<n>    sum_digit = 0<n>    while n < 3:<n>        digit = int(string[10-n])<n>        if n > 0:<n>

How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: 322<n><n>Input: Josh’s mom gives him $20 to go shopping at the mall. He buys a hat for $10 and a pencil for $2. Then he buys four cookies. If each cookie costs $1.25, how much money does Josh have left?<n>Output: 3<n><n>Input: George's bowling team is one round away from breaking the league record for most points scored in a season. The old record is an average score per player of 287 per round. Each team has 4 players and there are 10 rounds in the season. Through the first 9 rounds, his team has scored a total of 10,440. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. It took him 20 minutes to finish tasks from biology and two times more time to finish history. Geography took him the most time, three times more than history. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. If the pie left in the fridge weighs 1200 grams, how many grams did Sophia eat?<n>Output: 240<n><n>Input: Sarah, Mary, and Tuan decided to go to the restaurant for a meal. They decided to split the cost of the meal evenly. If the total price of the meal comes to $67 and they have a coupon for $4, how much does each person need to contribute to the bill?<n>Output: 21<n><n>Input: Tom's brother is 4 times as old as Tom's dog. If in 6 years, Tom's brother will be 30 years, how old is Tom's dog going to be in six years?<n>Output: 12<n><n>Input:East coast areas such as Florida are found where? Choices:  A: florida B: denmark C: united states D: map E: california<n>Output:		 Florida<n><n>Input:What was the last play in the game last scored? Choices: B: touchdown  C: extra point D: safety E: field goal<n>Output:  B<n><n>Input: Which of the following is correct? Choices: B A C D E<n>Output:  B <n><n>#import "PXProblems.m"<n><n><n>void printProblems(NSArray < PXProblem*> *problems, int nPXProblems){<n>	for (int i = 0; i < nPXProblems; ++i){<n>		NSLog(@"\n%@", [problems objectAtIndex:i]);<n>	}<n>	 NSLog(@"\n\n\n\t-------------------------------------------------------------------\n\n");<n>	<n>}<n>int main (int argc, const char * argv[]) {<n>    <n>    NSArray < PXProblem1*> *problems = [PXProblem1 problemArray];<n>	printProblems(problems, [problems count]);<n>	<n>    return 0;<n>}<n><n><n><n><n><n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers. The old record is an average score per player of 287 per round. Each team has 4 players and there are 10 rounds in the season. Through the first 9 rounds, his team has scored a total of 10,440. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. They decided to split the cost of the meal evenly. If the total price of the meal comes to $67 and they have a coupon for $4, how much does each person need to contribute to the bill?<n>Output: 21<n><n>Input: Tom's brother is 4 times as old as Tom's dog. If in 6 years, Tom's brother will be 30 years, how old is Tom's dog going to be in six years?<n>Output: 12<n><n>Input:What could listening to music cause you to be? Choices:  A: happy B: smile C: calm D: entertainment E: relaxation<n>Output:		A<n><n>Input:How many feet are in one mile? Choices: 12 feet 1200 feet 5040 feet<n>Output: 5040<n><n>Input:-140/-14/6= ___________<n>Output:-137<n><n>Input:John has 400 coins and wants to separate them into baskets of 500 coins. How many baskets does he need?<n>Output: 9<n><n>Input:Give the next number in the sequence, +18, -18, 038, 438, 697, 9??<n>Output: 1050<n><n>Input:What is the sum of the two prime numbers above?<n>Output: 7<n>

It means in 4 weeks Zach has 4*65 or 260 as a total money.<n><n>In one week, spending 2 hours, he can earn $32. So Zach has to spend 260 - 260 = 0 money. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: 322<n><n>Input: Josh’s mom gives him $20 to go shopping at the mall. He buys a hat for $10 and a pencil for $2. Then he buys four cookies. If each cookie costs $1.25, how much money does Josh have left?<n>Output: 3<n><n>Input: George's bowling team is one round away from breaking the league record for most points scored in a season. The old record is an average score per player of 287 per round. Each team has 4 players and there are 10 rounds in the season. Through the first 9 rounds, his team has scored a total of 10,440. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. It took him 20 minutes to finish tasks from biology and two times more time to finish history. Geography took him the most time, three times more than history. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. If the pie left in the fridge weighs 1200 grams, how many grams did Sophia eat?<n>Output: 240<n><n>Input: Sarah, Mary, and Tuan decided to go to the restaurant for a meal. They decided to split the cost of the meal evenly. If the total price of the meal comes to $67 and they have a coupon for $4, how much does each person need to contribute to the bill?<n>Output: 21<n><n>Input: Tom's brother is 4 times as old as Tom's dog. If in 6 years, Tom's brother will be 30 years, how old is Tom's dog going to be in six years?<n>Output: 12<n><n>Input:Eating breakfast with a large family leads to a pile of what in the sink? Choices:  A: fullness B: underwear C: bad breath D: better day E: dirty dishes<n>Output:		A<n><n>Input: In a baseball league there are 2 teams. Each game, the teams choose 11 players. Each player can play on the same team 2 times. How many players total can play on each team?<n>Output: A: 28 players B: 56 players C: 62 players D: 63 players E: None of the above<n><n>Input: The length and width of a boat are twice its height. How many squares of side length 2 measure into the hull of the length 32 feet?<n>Output: A : 9 B: 11 C: 9 D: 12 E: None of the Above<n><n>Input: How long does it take one person to fill one bucket with water. (the other bucket is full)<n>Output: A:3minutes B:4minutes C:5minutes D:6minutes E:none of the above<n><n><n>### Instruction:Answer the follow-up questions:<n><n><n><n>### 3. How many ways are there to order 4 people for dinner?<n><n>Solution :<n><n>Ordering 4 people with 4 people<n><n>1st option : K, P, Q, R<n><n>2nd option : T, P, Q, S<n><n>3rd option : K, P1, Q, R<n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: 322<n><n>Input: Josh’s mom gives him $20 to go shopping at the mall. He buys a hat for $10 and a pencil for $2. Then he buys four cookies. If each cookie costs $1.25, how much money does Josh have left?<n>Output: 3<n><n>Input: George's bowling team is one round away from breaking the league record for most points scored in a season. The old record is an average score per player of 287 per round. Each team has 4 players and there are 10 rounds in the season. Through the first 9 rounds, his team has scored a total of 10,440. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. It took him 20 minutes to finish tasks from biology and two times more time to finish history. Geography took him the most time, three times more than history. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. If the pie left in the fridge weighs 1200 grams, how many grams did Sophia eat?<n>Output: 240<n><n>Input: Sarah, Mary, and Tuan decided to go to the restaurant for a meal. They decided to split the cost of the meal evenly. If the total price of the meal comes to $67 and they have a coupon for $4, how much does each person need to contribute to the bill?<n>Output: 21<n><n>Input: Tom's brother is 4 times as old as Tom's dog. Choices:  A: michigan B: lake C: tide pool D: nursery E: atlantic ocean<n>Output:		A<n><n>input:1112333444555667771111112222232333344<n>output:12<n>imported from KMPC 2019

Choices:  A: dance like crazy B: standing still C: wallflower D: stand still E: like dancing<n>Output:		 C, Wallflower<n><n>Input:There were 360 students in Tom's class. After 3 days, only students who passed both subjects were left. How many students were left?<n>Output:324<n><n>Input: If a person has $30 left after buying 5 pizzas, how many pizzas can they buy if they have $25?<n>Output:10<n><n>Input: 8 apples + 5 oranges - 3 apples + 2 oranges = ___.<n>Output:19<n><n>Input: There are 8 cats. Three die on the way to the park. When there are already 8 cats in the park, two die in the park. How many cats were in the park?<n>Output: 7<n><n>Input: There is some number of apples and oranges. The sum of the squares of the apples is the same as the sum of the squares of one more than the oranges. Which of the following is equal to the sum of the squares?<n>A.) 36 + 1<n>B.) 12 + 2<n>C.) 7 + 2<n>D.) 8 + 2<n>E.) 24 + 2<n>Output: C. 24  + 2 = 26  is one more than  2  + 2 =  4  so  26 = 4 x  6  so  the sum of the 6 values of 2 is 6.     The values that give 6 + 2 must therefore be 12 + 10.<n><n>Input: 28 students take part in the relay. In the next four years there will be an increase of 2 students. How many students are there at that time in the relay?<n>Output: 56<n><n>Input: In order to get a good grade in Math, students need both to study diligently as well as to get good grades in the homework. The number of good homework grades a student got in the last lesson is 15. In which of the following grades the student receives a grade of 3.5 and 4 in the next lesson?<n>ChoiceA: (4 * 2 * 3.5) / (15 * 4 * 3 + 3) = 3.5

She  used 6 large stickers on the journal and 5 stickers each to 9 other pages in her journal,  and 5 stickers on the cover. How many stickers  does Mary have remaining? <n><n># Output: 8 stickers <n><n># Input: Zach is saving his <n><n># Output answer (6): Zach needs one more dollar. <n><n># Input : Mark<n># Output answer : Mark needs three more goats.<n># Input: George<n># Output answer : George needs ten more points.<n># Input: Max<n># Output answer : Max needs 20 more minutes.<n># Input: Sarah<n># Output answer : Sarah needs twelve more dollars.<n># Input: Josh<n># Output answer : Josh needs two more dollars.<n>#Input 5 <n><n># Input 10<n># Output answer 8<n><n># Input 5 <n><n>```<n><n>```<n># Solution<n># Time Complexity:   O(|M| + |A|) for the given M and A <n># Space Complexity:   O(1) <n># Method:   Use a stack <n># Input:   - stack - array of intervals<n># Output:   - number of subsets<n># Example:   - 9, 2, 5, 6, 7   - 4<n>```<n>---<n><n>## Answer for [question no 7](/README.md#instructions): <n><n># Solution<n>#  ASSUMPTION: You can take only one variable at a time. Let's assume you take the first <n>#  variable: `input = (M+A)/2`<n>#  So we'll have `output = input - sumO(i, A[i])`<n># <n>#   Example (A - set of positive integers and M - set of positive integers)<n>#   - 
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers. Students who use this program can either choose to swap classes with another student or with the teacher who gives that class. In some of the classes, the teacher has given out more than one schedule swap pass to a student. To make things more confusing, the students that use the passes may be students who have switched classes with the teacher. The table below shows the number of passes left

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: 322<n><n>Input: Josh’s mom gives him $20 to go shopping at the mall. He buys a hat for $10 and a pencil for $2. Then he buys four cookies. If each cookie costs $1.25, how much money does Josh have left?<n>Output: 3<n><n>Input: George's bowling team is one round away from breaking the league record for most points scored in a season. The old record is an average score per player of 287 per round. Each team has 4 players and there are 10 rounds in the season. Through the first 9 rounds, his team has scored a total of 10,440. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. It took him 20 minutes to finish tasks from biology and two times more time to finish history. Geography took him the most time, three times more than history. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. If the pie left in the fridge weighs 1200 grams, how many grams did Sophia eat?<n>Output: 240<n><n>Input: Sarah, Mary, and Tuan decided to go to the restaurant for a meal. They decided to split the cost of the meal evenly. If the total price of the meal comes to $67 and they have a coupon for $4, how much does each person need to contribute to the bill?<n>Output: 21<n><n>Input: Tom's brother is 4 times as old as Tom's dog. If in 6 years, Tom's brother will be 30 years, how old is Tom's dog going to be in six years?<n>Output: 12<n><n>Input:Which effect of stress could cause death if not treated immediately? Choices:  A: age grieving person B: heart attacks C: depression D: hair loss E: headache<n>Output:		A<n><n>Input: A mother gives birth to a baby.  The baby is exactly 4 weeks premature.  How many years apart are the boy and girl?<n>Output: 98<n><n>Input: A pizza shop has 75 large, 45 medium, and 4 cheese-only pizzas. If it sells cheese-only pizza at half the price of large or medium pizza, the cheese pizza will make up how many percent of the total profit?<n>Output: 82<n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. Choices:  A: earth B: movie C: party D: served cold E: freezer<n>Output:		D<n><n>Input: Sammy ate three pounds of cake yesterday. Today he had two times as much spaghetti. How much more food did Sammy eat today than the day before?<n>Output: 9 pounds<n><n>Input: Mary went to the zoo with $8 and spent $1.50 at the snack shop. How much money did she spend total?<n>Output: 8.50<n><n>Input: Mr. Smith has 30 apples in the garden, 50 pears, and 15 mangoes. How many apples does he have twice as many pears?<n>Output: 700<n><n>Input: Joe wanted 13 boxes of tissues. If a box of tissues costs $4 and if the total cost for 13 boxes was $78, how many boxes did he get for free?<n>Output: 5<n><n>Input: Lena had $7 in her piggy bank. She spent $1.25 to buy a book. She then saved $1.87. How much money did Lena save?<n>Output: 0<n><n>Input: Annie has a pen, two red pencils, three blue pencils and six green pencils. How many pencils does she have in all?<n>Output: <n><n>Input: Tom bought 60 bananas for $4.00. He ate 22 bananas at a time. How much money did he have to eat one banana?<n>Output:  19<n><n>Input: I had some cookies I wanted to give to my friends. If four times the number of the cookies were a multiple of 7, write down the number of cookies I had.<n>Output: 8

Cars don't.<n><n><n>```python<n><n># 📱 Input<n>answer_list = []<n><n>s = list(map(int, input().split()))<n>answer = max(s)<n>answer_list.append(answer)<n><n>print(answer)<n>```<n><n><n><n>#### ⚡️ Answer : D.<n><n><n><n>We can get the difference between the two values and then multiple that by the total number of levels on the bike.<n><n><n>```<n>answer = 44<n><n>diff = s[0] - s[1]<n><n>total_levels = s[0]<n><n>answer = diff * total_levels<n><n>print(answer == s[1])<n>```<n><n><n>    <n>    True<n>    <n><n><n><n>```<n><n>answer = 6<n><n>difference = s[0]-s[1]<n><n>diff = s - 6<n><n>total_level = 6<n><n>answer = difference * total_level<n><n>print( answer )<n>```<n><n><n>    True<n><n><n><n>```python <n><n>answer = 46<n><n>diff = s [0] - s [1]<n><n>total amount of stickers : s [0]<n><n>if s [0] == 89 ( True/ False ) : <n><n>   if diff == 2.0 : <n><n>       answer = 89 - 2 *3 * 6<n>       answer = 46 <n><n>          <n><n>

There's a specific way in which it deals with each problems that needs to be considered when solving.<n><n>What are all the possible options?<n>* 6 or under<n>* 7 or under<n>* 9<n><n>What are all of the valid cases?<n><n>* Mary did not use that many stickers<n>* Mary had that many stickers<n><n>How will you solve it?<n><n>In this lesson, a formula was taught. Choices:  A: health club B: jocks C: fitness centre D: stadium E: gymnasium<n>Output:		d<n><n>Input:What is the best choice to buy a good quality TV  A: electronics store B: online shopping C: shopping mall D: the supermarket E: any store<n>Output: b<n><n>Input:The best choice to buy clothing A: online shopping B: jocks E: the market<n>Output: d<n>Input:It will be cloudy today A: sunny B: hot C: gloomy D: sunless E: none of above<n>Output: d<n>```<n><n> <n><n>## Solution:<n><n>A = df['choice_a'] <n>B = df['choice_b']<n>C = df['choice_c']<n>D = df['choice_d']<n>E = df['choice_e']<n><n>df.loc['choice_best'] = (df.apply(lambda x: (x['answer_a'] == 'a', True), axis=1))<n>df.loc['other'] = (df.loc['choice','answer_b'].isin('b'))<n><n>df.drop(df[df.loc['choice'] == 'c'].index.tolist(), columns = ['choice_best'])<n><n><n>df.loc[df.loc['other'], 'choice_best'] = ['','']<n><n>df['best'] = df['choice_best'].str.contains('b')<n>df.loc[~df.loc['best'], 'best'] = df.loc['choice_a'].str.contains('(1) or '), 'b').str.contains('(2)')<n><n><n>df.head(10) <n><n><n><n><n><n>

In each round robin, each player plays one match against each of the other players.  After each round robin match, the players are given rankings, in the form of fractions, such that the numerator is the number of matches they won, and the denominator is the number of total matches played in the round robin. The number of players in a doubles tennis tournament is an even number and they all have different rankings.<n><n>For example, if five players are in the tournament, where "A" means first, "B" means second, and so on:<n><n>  -If player "A" has the largest fraction after the round robin match, then the answer is player "B".<n>  -If player “A” and player "B" have the largest and second largest fractions after the round robin, then the answer is either "A" or "B".<n>  If "A" and "B" have the greatest, the second greatest, and the third greatest fractions after the round <n>    robin match, then player
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: 322<n><n>Input: Josh’s mom gives him $20 to go shopping at the mall. He buys a hat for $10 and a pencil for $2. Then he buys four cookies. If each cookie costs $1.25, how much money does Josh have left?<n>Output: 3<n><n>Input: George's bowling team is one round away from breaking the league record for most points scored in a season. The old record is an average score per player of 287 per round. Each team has 4 players and there are 10 rounds in the season. Through the first 9 rounds, his team has scored a total of 10,440. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. It took him 20 minutes to finish tasks from biology and two times more time to finish history. Geography took him the most time, three times more than history. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. If the pie left in the fridge weighs 1200 grams, how many grams did Sophia eat?<n>Output: 240<n><n>Input: Sarah, Mary, and Tuan decided to go to the restaurant for a meal. They decided to split the cost of the meal evenly. If in 6 years, Tom's brother will be 30 years, how old is Tom's dog going to be in six years?<n>Output: 12<n><n>Input:What kind of driving leads to accidents? Choices:  A: stressful B: dangerous C: fun D: illegal E: deadly<n>Output:		 E<n><n>Input: What does the letter 'o' represent? Choices:  o - open space o - one <n><n>Output:  o - open<n><n>#### Solution:<n><n>### Answer 1:<n><n>You just solve the problem by hand:<n><n>- Mary started with 89 stickers<n>- used 3 on front and each page had 7<n>- remain with = (89 - 3 - 7*6) = 44 stickers<n><n>### Answer2:<n><n>Let's start with two basic equations:<n><n>$$ x + y = 100$$<n><n>$$ x + 2*y = 100$<n><n>We know x is the amount of money Zach has.<n><n>Solve each equation and you get:<n><n>$$ x = 100 - 2y$$.<n><n>So x is how much money he has left at the end.<n><n>To answer the question what is the amount of money he needs to earn from Saturday after babysitting to buy the bike, you just solve for how much he earns Saturday<n><n>- 100 - y = 6<n><n>- 11 + y = 6<n>- 11* 2/3 = 6<n><n>So he needs to babysit for another hour to have enough money to buy the bike. (He earns an extra $10 a babysit session)<n><n>### Answer3:<n><n>Let' time and L be the number of legs.<n>We want to find the number of legs. So:<n><n>$$ L = 2*time + babysit $$<n><n>We know the number of kangaroos and the number of goats. We want to know the number of legs:<n><n>\$$ L = K + G $$<n><n>$$ L = K + babysit + 3*K/(time + babysits)$$<n><n>$$ 2*K + 2*G + 3*K/2 = L$$<n><n>$$ G = 3*K/4 - L/2$$<n><n>As well as another equation:<n><n>$$ 4*K + L = 33 $$<n><n>So K = 23 or K = 7. <n><n>\$$G = (23(go

She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: 322<n><n>Input: Josh’s mom gives him $20 to go shopping at the mall. He buys a hat for $10 and a pencil for $2. Then he buys four cookies. If each cookie costs $1.25, how much money does Josh have left?<n>Output: 3<n><n>Input: George's bowling team is one round away from breaking the league record for most points scored in a season. The old record is an average score per player of 287 per round. Each team has 4 players and there are 10 rounds in the season. Through the first 9 rounds, his team has scored a total of 10,440. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. It took him 20 minutes to finish tasks from biology and two times more time to finish history. Geography took him the most time, three times more than history. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. If the pie left in the fridge weighs 1200 grams, how many grams did Sophia eat?<n>Output: 240<n><n>Input: Sarah, Mary, and Tuan decided to go to the restaurant for a meal. They decided to split the cost of the meal evenly. If the total price of the meal comes to $67 and they have a coupon for $4, how much does each person need to contribute to the bill?<n>Output: 21<n><n>Input: Tom's brother is 4 times as old as Tom's dog. If in 6 years, Tom's brother will be 30 years, how old is Tom's dog going to be in six years?<n>Output: 12<n><n>Input:If you aren't glad, unhappy or gloomy, what illness may you have? Choices:  A: depressed B: downcast C: angry D: unhappy E: sorrowful<n>Output:		A<n><n>Input: If you have fun, enjoyable and entertaining time, what are you engaged in? Choices:  E: Entertainment B: leisure D: Happiness

If in 6 years, Tom's brother will be 30 years, how old is Tom's dog going to be in six years?<n>Output: 12<n><n>Input:The person was looking up airline and hotel prices, what was he looking to do? Choices:  A: control computer B: separate things C: go on vacation D: cross street E: go out<n>Output:		B, go on vacation.<n><n>Input:The guy went out to get a haircut and shave. His haircut was 25 dollars. How much was his shave if its half of his haircut?<n>Output: $12.50<n><n>Input:The price of a car was $40 less than ten times the price of a pen, what is the price of the pen?<n>Output: $40<n><n>Input:"Please pick 2 out of 3," which implies 2X=3X and 2X+2X=3X+3X and 8X=9X, and so X=4<n><n>Input:Tom used to work on the same farm as John.  If 25 dollars and 80 cents per day represents half of what Tom used to earn and three hours of work, what is Tom's new salary per day?<n>Output: $23.50<n><n>#### Solution<n>```python<n>def solution(question_id):<n>    """<n>    Given a question ID, return its solutions<n>    """<n><n>    # Example:<n>    #(1) 3 (2) 15 (3) 0 (4) 0 (5) 3 (6) 21 (7) 28 (8) 8 (9) 26 (10) 14<n>    # Answer: 3<n>    <n>    # Convert input question ID to an index<n>    question_id = int(question_id)<n>    questions = [{'question_id': question_id} for i in range(3)]<n>    result = {}<n>    <n>    # Start the loop and return the answer<n>    for i in range(len(questions)):<n>        for j in range(len(quesations)):<n><n>            if (quesations[j]['question_id'] == questions[i]['question_id']):<n>                result[quesations[j]['id']] = i<n>    <n>    return result<n>```

Choices: A: Yes B: No<n>Output: A<n>Input: How many 4-digit numbers are divisible by 2 and 5? Choices: A: 5 B: 9 C: 14 D: 15 E: 20<n>Output: B<n><n>### Instruction:This is a math problem.  Try to answer it before reading this line.<n><n>Answer: There are 1000 numbers that are divisible by 15 and divisible by 2.  The number will be divisible by 2 if all or only the two digits are even.  The only way to get an "even" 4-digit number is to replace one of its digits with a zero.  So to get a number divisible by 2, you can take any 5-digit number and change only the last digit to a 0.  Once you have done that to the number, it needs to be divided by 5 and it becomes a 4-digit number.<n><n>So the total number of 4-digit numbers divisible by 2 is 500, the first 500 numbers on the 1-1000 number list.<n><n>There are 120 such numbers that are also divisible by 5.  To achieve this, a 4-digit divisible-by-5 number can use any of the digits that are not divisible by 2 because two of those digits must appear in the number.  So if the number ends in 8, you can add the letter d at the end.  Since letters are not divisible by two, the number is then divisible by 5, and the 5-digit number becomes 4-digit.   <n><n>So the total is (120 * 1000) + (500 * 50) = 60,000.<n><n>

How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: 322<n><n>Input: Josh’s mom gives him $20 to go shopping at the mall. He buys a hat for $10 and a pencil for $2. Then he buys four cookies. If each cookie costs $1.25, how much money does Josh have left?<n>Output: 3<n><n>Input: George's bowling team is one round away from breaking the league record for most points scored in a season. The old record is an average score per player of 287 per round. Each team has 4 players and there are 10 rounds in the season. Through the first 9 rounds, his team has scored a total of 10,440. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. It took him 20 minutes to finish tasks from biology and two times more time to finish history. Geography took him the most time, three times more than history. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. If the pie left in the fridge weighs 1200 grams, how many grams did Sophia eat?<n>Output: 240<n><n>Input: Sarah, Mary, and Tuan decided to go to the restaurant for a meal. They decided to split the cost of the meal evenly. If the total price of the meal comes to $67 and they have a coupon for $4, how much does each person need to contribute to the bill?<n>Output: 21<n><n>Input: Tom's brother is 4 times as old as Tom's dog. If in 6 years, Tom's brother will be 30 years, how old is Tom's dog going to be in six years?<n>Output: 12<n><n>Input:If you're traveling along a highway what item made of paper can you use to find your way? Choices:  A: united states B: atlas C: developed land D: park E: countryside<n>Output:		C<n>

Choices:  A: rural area B: big city C: suburbs D: ohio E: countryside<n>Output:		B<n><n>### Solution:<n>To solve this problem I first made note of any terms I didn't know, and used my notes to make assumptions about the answer. For Question 1, we do not know the specific number of stickers remaining, but if we subtract this from 89 which is the original number, we can determine this and then subtract the 89 that we started with and then we have the initial number of stickers. Then for Q3, we do know the exact number of stickers we have left and how much we can save, so we would just find how much it is going to take and how much is in the bank already? For Q4, the first thing I did was to get the answer 3, 2, 4, in that order because that would result in a total of 3 legs on the problem. Next, I used my notes to get me started with Q5. I multiplied 10,450-1283=8,967. 8,967/480=19. Because we are trying to take the average of 287, then we would want to divide this 19 I found to our average for that is the correct answer. For Q6, we know that every subject took us a particular amount of time, so we can use that information to figure out how much in total it took us to do math homework. Next, I multiplied the answer from Q7 to see what we had and it is 40. I then multiplied 40 by the grams left in the fridge to solve the question. Next I multiplied all of the amounts of money owed by each person and divided that by 120 to find out what needed to be paid by each person. For Q9 I know that our total is 67 and I know each person has one coupons. Now, I simply need to multiply 67 by 4 to find out how much each person is paying for the meal. For Q10, I know that now since Tom's brother is the same age as Tom, Tom's dog is going to be two years old.<n>#### Instructions<n>Answer the following multiple choice questions.<n>Input: Mary had `89 stickers`. How many chocolates are in green wrappers?<n>Output: 5 / Answer: The second chocolate is red and then three different colors are left (green, brown, and yellow). Since there are three of each color left we deduce that there are 3 greens, and 3 browns and 3 yellows. Thus there were originally 6 greens, 6 browns, and 6 yellows.<n>Output: 0<n><n><n>

How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. They decided to split the cost of the meal evenly. How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. Choices:  A: knife wounds B: buy a gun C: bleeding D: jail time E: law suit<n>Output:		Law Suit<n><n>Input:  The next level of the game is called Runic Rounds.The 30 stones in each player’s hand have 10 different shapes and 30 symbols. To win, players race to make as many matches of stone and symbol as possible.Players take a symbol out of their stone hand, then make a match by placing it onto one of the matching 10 stones in front of them. Each stone has two sides and each side can have one of 30 symbols displayed next to it. Players can pick any of the three symbols in the stone, but players can pick the same symbol only if they are on the same side.If you make a match with a stone, you can keep it. But if instead you make three matches of stones and symbols with any of the three symbols on the stones, the symbols stay on the stone and you can continue playing. For example, if a player puts three matches of stones and symbol in one turn, the symbols might all go on one stone, or one stone might be turned over and show three sets of symbols, or you might have two sets of matches with three stones each and so on. You may stack symbols on top of a stone to make a match.The game ends when a player runs out of stones. The player with the most matches wins.<n>Output: A<n><n>Input:  There are 30 cute puppy photos in this book. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: 322<n><n>Input: Josh’s mom gives him $20 to go shopping at the mall. He buys a hat for $10 and a pencil for $2. Then he buys four cookies. If each cookie costs $1.25, how much money does Josh have left?<n>Output: 3<n><n>Input: George's bowling team is one round away from breaking the league record for most points scored in a season. The old record is an average score per player of 287 per round. Each team has 4 players and there are 10 rounds in the season. Through the first 9 rounds, his team has scored a total of 10,440. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. It took him 20 minutes to finish tasks from biology and two times more time to finish history. Geography took him the most time, three times more than history. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. If the pie left in the fridge weighs 1200 grams, how many grams did Sophia eat?<n>Output: 240<n><n>Input: Sarah, Mary, and Tuan decided to go to the restaurant for a meal. They decided to split the cost of the meal evenly. If the total price of the meal comes to $67 and they have a coupon for $4, how much does each person need to contribute to the bill?<n>Output: 21<n><n>Input: Tom's brother is 4 times as old as Tom's dog. If in 6 years, Tom's brother will be 30 years, how old is Tom's dog going to be in six years?<n>Output: 12<n><n>Input:Where would you see people in uniform playing with a ball? Choices:  A: hole B: television C: sporting goods store D: pool table E: sporting event<n>Output:		Choice:  C -> Pool Table<n>

How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. They decided to split the cost of the meal evenly. How many games were needed to decided the winner?<n>Output:<n><n>### Task 1：Given a dollar amount (positive), subtract the number from 70 to determine whether or not the specified amount has been reached in order to get a discount or not.<n><n>Input: a = 50<n>Output: a % 70 = 50 % 70<n><n>Input: a=25<n>Output: a %70 = 25 % 70<n>```<n><n>### Task2：Given a number (positive or negative) in the range from 70-185, subtract the number from 190 to determine whether or <n><n>	not the specified amount has been spent and the person is qualified for a discount<n><n>```<n>Input:<n>a= -5<n>Output:<n>a %190 = -5 % 190<n>```<n><n><n>```python<n>def main():<n>    with open("./data/in.txt") as input, open("./data/out.txt", "w") as output:<n>        for line in input.readlines():<n>            line = line.split('\n')<n>            a_number = line[1]<n>            answer = line[2]<n>            if a_number.isdigit()!= 0 and -110 < int(a_number) <= 120:<n>                # -115 < amount < 125<n>                if a_number <= 85:<n>                    answer =  abs(int(a_number))%70-70<n>                    output.write(f'\nInput  : {a_number}\n')<n>                    output.writelines(f'Output: {answer}\n')<n>                    <n>                    # Output: Output: Output:<n>                    # If  <=85, output 85%70, not 70%85<n>                    # If > 85, output 70%80<n>                else:<n>                    amount =  abs

She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn. If each cookie costs $1.25, how much money does Josh have left?<n>Output: 3<n><n>Input: George's bowling team is one round away from breaking the league record for most points scored in a season. The old record is an average score per player of 287 per round. Each team has 4 players and there are 10 rounds in the season. Through the first 9 rounds, his team has scored a total of 10,440. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. It took him 20 minutes to finish tasks from biology and two times more time to finish history. Geography took him the most time, three times more than history. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. If the pie left in the fridge weighs 1200 grams, how many grams did Sophia eat?<n>Output: 240<n><n>Input: Sarah, Mary, and Tuan decided to go to the restaurant for a meal. They decided to split the cost of the meal evenly. If the total price of the meal comes to $67 and they have a coupon for $4, how much does each person need to contribute to the bill?<n>Output: 21<n><n>Input: Tom's brother is 4 times as old as Tom's dog. If in 6 years, Tom's brother will be 30 years, how old is Tom's dog going to be in six years?<n>Output: 12<n><n>Input:What would a person do if he or she just woke up? So the woman tries: "I'm Twix, because I come between two people and we need to keep each other together." "Oh no!" The interviewer reponds. "I don't like Twixes." Later, the woman tries another: "I'm like Snickers, because I come with almonds and peanuts, which reminds people that we're not just candy bars but we also have other benefits such as vitamins and minerals." This time the interview takes the challenge. "No," he declares. "Snickers do not get my vote." So the woman's third try: "Oh... I can't think of one right now, but can I take it under advisement and call you next week?" "Of course," says the interviewer. "Now, can you tell me why you are really here?"<n>Output: A: The one who said, "I'm Twizler."<n><n>Input: Choose the odd one<n>Output: B<n><n>Input: The man said on his first visit, he asked, "Are you a man or a woman?"
